>>139321945
>your native language
Swememe

>Have you heard an English speaker attempt to speak your lang?
Yes, several times and many different Anglophones.

>What mistakes do they make?
Primarily idiomaticity (expressing themselves as if they were speaking English), and then the most tangible things are word order (V2 is apparently difficult), confusing parts-of-speech, and various grammatical agreements. Beginners also tend to have a hard time grasp definite nouns, and want to use articles instead. Another thing which isn't unique to Anglophones, but still a very Anglocentric thing, and is part of the idiomaticity problem, is to gloss a word and use it in all contexts; if English word A can be used in context 1 and 2, they gloss EWA for TL word A, but apply it to both contexts despite it not working that way in the TL.

>What letters are they bad at pronouncing?
How can you be bad at pronouncing a letter? Letters are relative. Various phonemes, however, are hard for non-natives. English doesn't have /y/, so beginners or learners without keen ears will turn this into an /i/, and /ɧ/ is unique to the language and substituted with various approximations, such as /h/ or /ʃ/, or even /x/. Anglophones also typically struggle with pure vowels, and their attempts are usually slightly diphthongized even when they really try to suppress them, but that isn't unique to Swememe learners, obv. I also wont bring up /r/, since it also isn't unique, but I've heard speakers slip into [ɹ].

Another thing, which is really hard to master so I usually don't criticize people for it, is of course the pitch accent.

>Can you understand them?
Depends on their level or proficiency. I've talked to some Scottish guy who spoke really well and only made like 1 or 2 mistakes during our conversation, and he could understand my kinda-drunk mumbly speech and non-standard dialect. And then I've talked to people I literally couldn't even comprehend even if I tried, and then various in-betweens there.

>Do native English speakers sound silly, stupid, cute, etc when speaking your language?
Uhm... Idk, I'm too used to it, I guess. I guess the intention (and the effort tied to said intention) dictates how I feel about it. I constructively criticize an active learner, but cringe to shit when some Anglo butchers it in some movie or something.

Also, refer to my point about the pitch accent. Every non-native, Anglophone or not, without enough exposure to get the hang of it sounds robotic and stiff, and, depending on the word, confusing.

And every learner has to go through learner their target language's prosody, and it's not unique to this situation.

Idk, sorry for my disappointing posts lmao.

100%-Extremely Common (Bulgaria, Italy, USA)
90-99%-Common (Hong Kong, Luxembourg, Iraq)
75-90%-Uncommon (Kenya, Pakistan, Nepal)
50-75%-Semi-Rare (Qatar, Mongolia, Guadeloupe)
25-50%-Rare (Kosovo, Guam, Malawi)
10-25%-Extremely Rare (Mauritius, Botswana, Andorra)
1-10%-Legendary (Gabon, Haiti, Saint Martin)
.001-1%-Mythical (Pitcairn, Nauru, Holy See)
<.001%-Ascended (Heard & McDonald, South Georgia & South Sandwich, Bouvet Island, USMOI)

It depends a lot on what exactly the flag is:
If it's just a square: resize to 16x11 and apply gloss
If it's a CoA that can be translated into a square flag: make a flag out of it (how labour intensive this is depends on the CoA in question)
If it's a CoA that can't be flagified (communist heraldry and a lot of South American/African CoAs fall under this): resize and stick it on a white background
Seal/logo/etc.: stick it on a white background
Irregularly shaped flag: resize and modify the gloss to suit the shape of the flag

com:
I've been thinking about the new iceberg map a lot. Can attendance rate really be used to determine how rare a flag is? One week a flag could have a 0.1% attendance rate but another week it could have a 1% attendance rate. Plus /bant/ and /sp/ screw over the attendance rates because some of their threads take days to finally die (e.g. that Barbados anon who sometimes posts in /sp/ but his posts usually stay alive for many days). You could argue that the boosted attendance rate is accurate because it means more people are going to be exposed to the rare flag since the thread is more active. A rare flag in a thread with 300 replies is going to be seen more than a rare flag in a thread with 30 replies.

The map says flags with a 1-4% attendance rate are posted every few weeks. Hypothetically that is false since a 1-4% attendance rate means they are posted every 100 to 25 hours (both are less time than a week). In reality, a lot of the 1-4% flags are never posted at that rate. Attendance rate is in constant flux, it always changes. It cannot be relied upon to determine how rare a flag truly is. Relying on post count to determine rarity is also wrong since it doesn't show how rare a flag currently is. For example, a flag could be posted 450 times in 2019 but only 50 times in 2020. Should it be put in the same category as a flag posted 250 times in 2019 and 250 times in 2020?

Kiribati, for example, has a 1.027% attendance rate. It has been posted 222 times since 23/12/19 (when the current attendance count started), mostly around Nov 2020. It has not been posted since then. So why would this flag be in the same category as the true 1% flags? It was obviously a proxyfag spamming pol and bant during the election that ruined the attendance rate. This kind of stuff just proves that flag rarity can never be truly determined without analysing the posts yourself. Making a true iceberg map is a more difficult task than I realised. Do you guys have any opinions on this?

Sì, ma come nell'esempio della signora col televisore che "non funziona", le parole sono uno strumento possibilmente imperfetto. La signora non sa dire "malfunzionamento" o "mancata accensione": per lei qualsiasi problema è un "non funziona".
Pensa quanta diagnostica a telefono avrebbe dovuto fare il povero tecnico per arrivare a capire che un tasto del telecomando non dava segni di vita: "il televisore non funziona", alias "il tasto 8 non mi cambia i canali che contengono 8".

Quando una terminologia viene usata molto spesso, viene convenzionalmente accettata da tutti. E quindi, per esempio, il parlare di "autogoal", anche in senso figurato, non dà luogo ad equivoci.
Così come "sacrificio", così come il "descendit", eccetera. Nel loro campo, non danno luogo ad equivoci - c'è una vastissima e plurimillenaria* letteratura teologica, e un somaro vien qui a metterla in dubbio, forte dell'aver letto qualche roba di qualcuno più asino ragliante di lui.

*) nota: "plurimillenaria" si usa anche per dire "qualcosa durato più di mille anni", non necessariamente "qualcosa durato più di enne migliaia di anni con enne appartenente agli interi positivi compresi fra due e più infinito".

Dharmakshetra as a manifestation of Divine Love, was established by Bhagwan Sri Sathya Sai Baba at Mumbai on May 12, 1968, on the eve of the First World Conference of Sri Sathya Sai Seva Organisation.
Thousands from all parts of India and even overseas witnessed the Inauguration. From far-flung lands they came, wafted by winds of grace. More than fifty thousand eager souls gathered that evening at the Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan Campus at Versova, Bombay, to express their joy at the momentous occasion. The magnificent structure was completed in 108 days after the first trowel of concrete was laid! The number 9 being the theme of the holy structure, of the 18 petals of the lotus which encloses the apartments where Bhagawan would stay, of the pillars, steps and trellis squares, all in multiples of 9, the Brahma Number.
Sri P.K. Sawant reminded the audience that Baba blessed Maharasthra while in His previous body at Shirdi, and it is Maharashtra's good fortune again that His Dharmakshetra has been established here itself. Baba said that every one is living, moving, acting and accumulating merit or demerit as a consequence, in kuru-kshetra, for, 'Kuru" means 'to do'. In this process, if the current of Dharma illumines every moment of life, then the Kurukshetra becomes Dharmakshetra. This, he said, will be the lesson that Dharmakshetra will radiate round the world.Baba took up residence at Sathya Deep, the rotunda with the lotus above and a moat filled with water all around; the place immediately became a hive of spiritual activity, a prolific purveyor of sweetness and light. There, children brought together in Sathya Sai Baba Vihars, boys and girls of the Seva Dal, adult workers in the Bhajan Mandalis and Seva Samithis, all receive Love and learn reverence. Baba speaks to them in groups, seekers and social workers who gather in the Prayer Hall; and they return with a deeper understanding and wider outlook.

name: Anonymous
com:
>>139266510
だって is a bound particle attaching to に here in the same way you might attach a は or も. だって has an "even" meaning kind of like でも.
>所謂「死相」というものに…もっと何か表情なり印象なりがある
what is called a "死相" has more of something like an expression or impression
attach でも to the first part to get the "even"

だろうに has a kind of "even though" nuance as a conjunction
I could only find this one sketchy site if you need an English reference to believe me
https://learnjapanesedaily.com/japanese-grammar-%E3%81%A0%E3%82%8D%E3%81%86%E3%81%AB-darouni.html
but with the だろう it's like "it's probably like this, right" and then the に makes the previous part like a preface to what comes after, usually with an implied "but"

I could maybe translate the whole thing like
>You'd think that, even with a so-called "death mask," there'd be more of an expression to it of some sort, or at least some kind of lasting impression that it would make on you... This is more like what you'd get if you just nailed a random horse's head to a human's body.

The only way to learn 日本語:
1.無理があんのよ
2.Don't waste time/money on ゴミ like:
-Shitty apps, 英語 youtube channels, Genki, Imabi, RTK, KKLC, Kanji Damage, Wanikani, Duolingo, language schools, AJATT, JLPT, Kanji Kentei tests and other scams
-Awful anki decks (only 2k/6k from the OP and a simple yomichan mining deck are ok)
-You shouldn't spend more than 1-2 hours on Anki as a beginner and 20 minutes max after a few months, spamming easy is fine, Anki is only good at the start to prepare you for the journey
-Pitch accent (doesn't exist, you can say words however you want http://kisu.me/1kiU )
-Learning how to write on paper (you can do it later once you're decent at Japanese)
Avoiding these beginner traps will cut down your learning time considerably to less than 5 years if you learn every day and never give up, since the following points are what actually teaches you Japanese
3.Take care of yourself, get some vitamins, read cosmetic ingredients, switch fluoride for hydroxyapatite, opt for natural ingredients if possible
4.Spend a few days getting familiar with hiragana and katakana
5.A few months of Anki 2k/6k vocabulary and Tae Kim grammar while reading something easy on the side
6.A few years of reading, listening, watching vtubers, shitposting in /djt/ and having your posts corrected by Jap flags, googling stuff you don't know and you're done!
7.Play Umineko
8.Move to Japan
9.Realize there's always more to learn and the ride never ends

>>139315959
(もし)~場合(は) is used to express an assumption and means ”if ~”, "when ~", "supposing it's the case that ~", "in the case that ~", and things like that.
In this usage, 場合 is basically interchangeable with 時.

>もしその台風が日本に上陸した場合、何が起こるだろう?
>もしその台風が日本に上陸した時、何が起こるだろう?
>What would happen if the typhoon made landfall in Japan?

On the other hand, こと means a (abstract) thing.

>これは重要なことだ
>This is an important thing.

>What I can do for the mother is to take care of her children
>私がその母親のためにできることは、子供たちの面倒を見ることだ
